  The passage discusses two theories about how communication between neurons is possible.
  The first theory suggests that electrical impulses travel from one neuron to the next by leaping across synapses.
  The second theory suggests that electrical impulses are transmitted between neurons chemically rather than electrically.

  The receptors for neurotransmitters contain both a neurotransmitter binding site and a separate region that functions as a channel for ions.

  The receptors for neurotransmitters display enough similarities to constitute a family, known collectively as neurotransmitter-gated ion channels.
  Each of the receptors in this family comes in several varieties so that subtle differences among the receptors for these chemicals may permit the selective treatment of certain brain disorders.
  Therefore, the main point of the passage is that evidence shows that electrical impulses are transmitted between neurons chemically rather than electrically, and that subtle differences among the receptors for these chemicals may permit the selective treatment of certain brain disorders.
